Rank Based Test Example

Mann-Whitney U (non-parametric alternative to an unpaired 2-sample t-test)

H0: equal ranks (or medians) HA: Ranks are not equal (or, medians are not equal)

Create Samples

set.seed() to create psuedorandom, but reproducible samples

set.seed(1414)
gp_1 <- sample.int(20, size = 15, replace = TRUE)

set.seed(1424)
gp_2 <- sample.int(30, size = 15, replace = TRUE)

Take a quick look at the distributions using hist().

hist(gp_1)

hist(gp_2) #both of these data sets do not look like they are closely following a normal distribution

Try a t-test so that we can compare the results:

ttest <- t.test(gp_1, gp_2)

# If these data were paired, I can just add the argument `paired = TRUE` within the t.test function

This p-value means that IF our samples are drawn from populations with the same mean (i.e.if the null hypothesis is true), there is a 0 probability of finding sample means at least as different as mine by random chance.

[ A more comprehensive explanation of difference between groups actually means, data spread, effect size] there is no signficant different (t(df) = t-statistic value, p = ).

We use the wilcox.test() function

mwu <- wilcox.test(gp_1, gp_2)
## Warning in wilcox.test.default(gp_1, gp_2): cannot compute exact p-value with
## ties

This p-value means that if our samples are drawn from a population with the same median, there is a 28% chance of finding sample medians at least as different as ours by random chance.

No significant difference in medians (Mann-Whitney U; U = 86, p = 0.28).

Example text for reporting: "The medians of group A (M = 22.4 g) and group B (M = 31.2 g) did not differ significantly (Mann Whitney U,)

Simple Linear Regression

Two continuous quantitative variables that you are trying to understand the relationship between, and you think that a linear relationship makes sense.

Use the penguins data from {palmerpenguins}, exploring flipper length (x) verses body mass (y). Does this data look like a linear relationship makes sense?

# Use View(penguins) to look at it 
#make an exploratory scatterplot of penguin flipper length (x-axis) verses body mass (y-axis)

ggplot(data = penguins,
       aes(x = flipper_length_mm,
           y = body_mass_g)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

## Find the model estimates (coefficients)

Use the lm() function for linear model.

body_mass_g ~ <<<<< tilde (not a minus sign)

penguin_lm <- lm(body_mass_g ~ flipper_length_mm, data = penguins)

Model Coefficients: -5780.8313581, 49.6855664 Flipper length coefficient: 49.6855664

Use broom::tidy() to get a tidy output from lm()

penguin_lm_tidy <- tidy(penguin_lm)

penguin_lm_tidy
## # A tibble: 2  5
##   term              estimate std.error statistic   p.value
##   <chr>                <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)        -5781.     306.       -18.9 5.59e- 55
## 2 flipper_length_mm     49.7      1.52      32.7 4.37e-107

Use broom::glance() to get output of model fit & statistical significance

penguin_lm_glance <- glance(penguin_lm)

penguin_lm_glance
## # A tibble: 1  12
##   r.squared adj.r.squared sigma statistic   p.value    df logLik   AIC   BIC
##       <dbl>         <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1     0.759         0.758  394.     1071. 4.37e-107     1 -2528. 5063. 5074.
## #  with 3 more variables: deviance <dbl>, df.residual <int>, nobs <int>
penguin_lm_tidy$estimate[2]
## [1] 49.68557

Use equatiomatic::extract_eq() to return model in LaTeX

extract_eq(model = penguin_lm, use_coefs = TRUE)

\[ \operatorname{\widehat{body\_mass\_g}} = -5780.83 + 49.69(\operatorname{flipper\_length\_mm}) \]
